@NODE Introduction "Introduction"

                             Introduction
                             ------------

I  needed  a  program like TrackSave for programming trackloaded games
and  demonstrations.  I  was very upset about the fact that I found no
satisfying  way  to  automatically  install  the current version of my
project  to  disk  by simply executing a batch file or ARexx script. I
had  to  enter a program called AsmOne in order to load all data areas
into  raw  memory, and then to write them to disk using the WT command
one  after the other. That was a very nasty procedure, especially when
changes of the disk segmentation became necessary. Another problem was
that  I  always  had  to  assemble  the disk on a physical floppy disk
drive.  It  would've been much more intelligent to fix it on a virtual
floppy (such as RAD or FMS by Matt Dillon/Jim Cooper) and then to copy
it  to  a  physical  disk  using a fully-featured disk copier (such as
SuperDuper by Sebastiano Vigna).

Using  TrackSave, I just need to execute a batch file or AREXX program
for  installing  all  data associated with my project to a physical or
virtual  disk.  As the name suggests, TrackSave writes tracks to disks
using the trackdisk.device. In addition to that, it can handle devices
similar  to  the  trackdisk.device, such as FMS or RAD. Don't expect a
sophisticated  GUI or something mystical like that, for TrackSave is a
simple  shell  tool. Last not least, TrackSave offers an exotic option
which  artificially  lengthens  disk  archives   and   an   option for
specifying an offset within your data file.

