@NODE Shell_usage "Shell usage"

                             Shell usage
                             -----------

Template:        TrackSave   FILE/A,U=UNIT/N,S=START/N,L=LEN/N,
                             R=RANDOM/S,O=OFFSET/N,D=DEVICE
                             

FILE

File to tracksave.


UNIT (U)

Drive  unit  number,  e.g. 2 for DF2: or FF2:, depending on the device
you are using. Default is 0.
         

START (S)

Starting track number, default is 0.


LEN (L)

Number of tracks to write. If you omit the LEN argument, the number of
tracks  depends  on the file length. Keep in mind that START + LEN may
not exceed 80 tracks if LEN is specified.


RANDOM (R)

If  the  RANDOM option is set and the file length does not fit exactly
into  a multiple of tracks (11264 bytes), the surplus memory is filled
up with random data instead of zeros. Keep in mind that disk archivers
usually  can't gain a single byte out of random data. You can use this
option  in order to lengthen disk archives which are the usual way for
spreading  trackloaded  disks  in  bulletin  board systems ;-) Default
setting is off.


OFFSET (O)

This  numeric argument enables you to define a byte offset within your
data  file,  thus  allowing you to skip a given number of bytes before
writing. Default is 0.


DEVICE (D)

This  argument  allows  you  to  specify   a   device   different from
trackdisk.device.  It should be trackdisk-like, such as fmsdisk.device
for floppy partitions or ramdrive.device for RAD. It is not adviced to
use  devices  like  audio.device or stuff like that anyway. Default is
trackdisk.device.



@ENDNODE

@NODE Examples "Examples"

                               Examples
                               --------

TrackSave dh0:data.raw         

tracksaves the file dh0:data.raw to DF0:, starting with track 0.


TrackSave dh0:data.raw UNIT 2 LEN 50

tracksaves  the  file  dh0:data.raw  to  DF2:,  starting with track 0,
length  is  50  tracks.  If  data.raw  is  smaller than 50 tracks, the
surplus  memory  is  filled  with  zeros  before   writing. Otherwise,
data.raw is cut at byte offset 563200 (50*11264).


TrackSave dh0:data.raw S=10 R D=ramdrive.device

tracksaves  the  file dh0:data.raw to RAD:, starting with track 10. If
data.raw  does  not fit exactly in a multiple of tracks (11264 bytes),
surplus memory is filled with random data.


TrackSave dh0:data.raw 2 d fmsdisk.device o 10000 l 40 s 10 r

tracksaves  the  file  dh0:data.raw  starting  with  offset   10000 to
fmsdisk-device  FF2:.  Length  is  40  tracks,  start  is track 10. If
data.raw minus 10000 does not fit exactly in 450560 bytes (40 tracks),
surplus  memory is filled with random data. If data.raw minus 10000 is
greater than 40 tracks, it is cut at (its total) offset 460560.


